The paper deals with the bin packing problem, which is a classic problem in computer science and falls under the category of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The fact that the problem is solved in polynomial time suggests that it may also be relevant to computational complexity theory (cs.CC). The use of polytopes and integer points suggests that the paper may also be relevant to discrete mathematics (cs.DM) and graph theory (cs.GT). Finally, the paper's focus on scheduling problems suggests that it may also be relevant to machine learning (cs.LG).
